# flotilla-dash host paths — consumed by deploy/flotilla-dash-install.sh to generate
# ~/.config/systemd/user/flotilla-dash.service from deploy/flotilla-dash.service.in.
#
# SETUP (one-time per host):
#   cp deploy/flotilla-dash.env.example deploy/flotilla-dash.env
#   $EDITOR deploy/flotilla-dash.env              # set the paths for THIS host
#   bash deploy/flotilla-dash-install.sh          # generate + install the unit (daemon-reload)
#   systemctl --user enable --now flotilla-dash   # the installer PRINTS this — you run it
#
# deploy/flotilla-dash.env is gitignored: these are filesystem paths (NOT secrets),
# but the layout is per-host, so each host keeps its own. To change paths later, edit
# this file and re-run the installer — never hand-edit the installed unit.
#
# Paths may use the systemd specifier %h (your home directory): the installer passes it
# through literally and systemd resolves it at runtime. Absolute paths also work.
# Values are taken LITERALLY — do NOT quote them (`KEY=%h/x`, not `KEY="%h/x"`);
# whitespace around the `=` is trimmed, but surrounding quotes are not stripped.
#
# This file holds PATHS, not secrets. If a future phase (the token-gated non-loopback
# bind) needs an auth token, it belongs in the secrets file referenced by
# FLOTILLA_DASH_SECRETS (chmod 600) — never as a value key here.

# Working directory for tidy `systemctl --user status flotilla-dash` output. The dash
# reads its config by the absolute paths below, so this rarely matters functionally.
FLOTILLA_DASH_WORKDIR=%h

# The flotilla binary. The `go install` default is %h/go/bin/flotilla.
FLOTILLA_DASH_BIN=%h/go/bin/flotilla

# Roster (same one watch/status use). The dash resolves the snapshot / ack / backlog
# paths from the roster's DIRECTORY, so only the roster path is needed for the read surface.
FLOTILLA_DASH_ROSTER=%h/.config/flotilla/flotilla.json

# Bind address. Default LOOPBACK. A non-loopback bind (0.0.0.0 / a LAN IP) is PERMITTED on
# a trusted private network (operator override): reads serve openly to the LAN, while
# state-changing writes stay CSRF-gated. For remote viewing without exposing the LAN,
# SSH-tunnel the loopback bind:  ssh -N -L 8787:127.0.0.1:8787 you@host  → http://127.0.0.1:8787
FLOTILLA_DASH_BIND=127.0.0.1:8787

# OPTIONAL — write-gate origin allowlist (comma-separated), REQUIRED for writes on a
# non-loopback (LAN) bind. Declare the EXACT origin(s) you browse the dash from, e.g.
# http://192.168.1.50:8787 — the write gate accepts only these, validated against this
# fixed list and NEVER against the request Host header (which an attacker controls in a
# DNS-rebinding attack). A LAN bind with none set fails closed for writes (reads still work).
#FLOTILLA_DASH_ALLOWED_ORIGINS=http://192.168.1.50:8787

# OPTIONAL — the GitHub repo (owner/name) for the native issue tracker. When SET, the
# generated unit gains `--repo <owner/name>`; when UNSET (leave commented), the dash
# resolves the working-dir repo the way `gh` does, or disables the tracker with a clear
# message. The tracker reuses gh's existing host auth — NO token here.
#FLOTILLA_DASH_REPO=owner/name

# OPTIONAL — the secrets env file (chmod 600) for the operator-note webhook. When SET,
# the unit gains `--secrets <path>` and the Control tab's note action posts to Discord;
# when UNSET (leave commented), the note action is disabled with a clear message and the
# rest of the dash is unaffected. Same file watch uses (FLOTILLA_WEBHOOK_<AGENT> lines).
#FLOTILLA_DASH_SECRETS=%h/.config/flotilla/flotilla-secrets.env

# OPTIONAL — insecure mode: set DISABLE_AUTHENTICATION=1 in the dash unit's environment
# (systemd drop-in) to disable write-route CSRF gates entirely until bearer auth (#208)
# lands. Prefer declaring FLOTILLA_DASH_ALLOWED_ORIGINS (above) for a LAN bind — that keeps
# the CSRF gate ON — and use this only as a last resort on a fully-trusted network.
#DISABLE_AUTHENTICATION=1
